Prompt Level: 7.0 Prompt: Your boss has sent you an email, asking you to prepare a presentation about the company. Read the email and draft a speech. Include an introduction, a body (with signposting phrases, where possible), an anecdote and a call to action. Write 150–250 words. Response: As you know, I need your help preparing a short presentation about the company for recruits. Can you write up a short speech?  Try to make it engaging; i don't want just a boring list of facts. Some key points to include:
1. Frisko Shipping was founded in 2001 by Bill Frisko;
2.locations in 20 cities all over the world;
3.more than 5,000 employees;
4.our profit of 5 million dollars last year and 10 percent of the global market;
5.New employees are expected to be motivated and enthusiastic.
It might be useful to hold a quiz too see how much they already know about the company.
They might want to know something about me, so you can tell them about the time that the passing ship that saved my life inspired me to start my own shipping company. Hopefully they'll see that as evidence that they can find inspiration anywhere.

Prompt Level: 13.0 Prompt: You are writing to Harry, a new manager in your company. He wants advice on how to effectively motivate his team and what strategies to avoid. Use the language and strategies you have learned in this lesson. Type in the input box. Write 150-200 words. Response: Hi Harry,
Hope you are doing well. We are really happy that you joined our management team. According to your question, I would be happy to share our advices how we are motivating our teams in our company.
Here is some tips and tricks what could be used:
*Create a clear  and possible to achieve goals and share your expectations on the deliveries;
*Provide regular feedback, which will help team members understand their strengths and areas for improvements;
*Empower your team, giving them autonomy to make decisions and take ownership of their work;
*Always celebrate successes, even small achievements! As this boosts morale and motivation;
*Communicate effectively and in understandable way
Also it is important to note what you should try to avoid:
*Micromanaging is not the best idea, as people don't like to be controlled in each step;
*Avoid difficult conversations
*Overpromise and underdeliver
Hope these tips help you navigate your new role as a manager and inspire your team to achieve great things! If you have any specific questions or need further advice, feel free to ask.

Best regards,
J.
